performance.response:
Natural selection is the process by which populations of organisms change over time because individuals with certain heritable traits tend to survive and reproduce more successfully than others. Here’s how it works:

1. Variation exists in every population  
   • Individuals differ in physical characteristics (size, color, shape) and behaviors.  
   • Much of this variation is due to differences in genes.

2. Some traits help individuals survive or reproduce  
   • A “helpful” trait might let an animal find food more easily, escape predators, or tolerate extreme temperatures.  
   • In plants, a helpful trait might be deeper roots to reach water or leaves shaped to catch more sunlight.

3. Differential survival and reproduction  
   • Individuals with advantageous traits (higher “fitness”) tend to live longer and produce more offspring.  
   • Those offspring inherit many of the same advantageous traits.

4. Traits become more common over generations  
   • As each generation passes, the helpful traits accumulate in the population.  
   • Less helpful or harmful traits become rarer.

5. Populations adapt to their environments  
   • Over many generations, the population as a whole becomes better suited to its environment.  
   • If environments change, new traits may become advantageous and be selected for.

Example:  
• Peppered moths in 19th-century England were originally light-colored and well camouflaged against light tree bark. When industrial soot darkened the bark, darker moths survived predation more often than light moths. Over time, the population shifted toward the dark form.  
• Once pollution controls cleaned the trees again, the lighter form regained its advantage.

Key points to remember:  
• Natural selection requires variation, heritability, and differences in reproductive success.  
• It acts on individuals but its consequences appear in populations over many generations.  
• It is the driving force behind adaptation and the diversity of life on Earth.

performance.response:
Natural selection is the process by which populations become better suited to their environments over successive generations. It works through four key principles:

1. Variation  
   • Individuals in a population differ from one another (size, coloration, disease resistance, etc.).  
   • Much of this variation is genetic—passed from parents to offspring.

2. Heritability  
   • Beneficial traits must be heritable so they can be passed on.  
   • If a trait improves survival or reproduction, offspring are more likely to inherit it.

3. Differential Survival and Reproduction  
   • Organisms with advantageous traits tend to survive longer and produce more offspring.  
   • Those without the traits leave fewer descendants.

4. Change in Allele Frequencies  
   • Over generations, alleles that confer an advantage increase in frequency within the gene pool.  
   • Less advantageous alleles become rarer.

Example: Peppered Moths  
• Before industrial pollution, light-colored moths blended in with lichened trees and avoided predators.  
• As soot darkened tree bark, dark-colored (“melanic”) moths had better camouflage.  
• Dark moths survived at higher rates, reproduced more, and their genes became common.

Types of Natural Selection  
• Directional Selection – Favors one extreme of a trait (e.g., darker coloration).  
• Stabilizing Selection – Favors intermediate traits and reduces extremes (e.g., average birth weight).  
• Disruptive Selection – Favors extremes at both ends (e.g., very large or very small beaks).

Outcomes of Natural Selection  
• Adaptation: Populations develop features that fit their environments (camouflage, toxin resistance, drought tolerance).  
• Speciation: Given enough time and isolation, accumulated differences can lead to new species.  
• Environmental Response: Populations can shift allele frequencies in response to changing conditions (climate change, new predators or diseases).

In sum, natural selection is the engine of evolutionary change. By favoring heritable traits that enhance survival and reproduction, it shapes the diversity of life and drives the emergence of new species.

performance.response:
Natural selection is the process by which heritable traits that confer a survival or reproductive advantage become more common in a population over successive generations. Here’s how it works and why it matters:

1. Variation  
   • Within any population, individuals differ genetically—for example, in coloration, size, metabolism or behavior.  
   • These differences arise through mutations, gene shuffling during sexual reproduction, and other genetic processes.

2. Inheritance  
   • Many of these trait differences are passed from parents to offspring via DNA.  
   • Only heritable (genetic) traits can be shaped directly by natural selection.

3. Differential Survival and Reproduction (Fitness)  
   • In a given environment, some trait variants help individuals survive longer or reproduce more effectively.  
   • “Fitness” is a measure of an individual’s reproductive success relative to others in the population.  
   • Individuals with higher fitness leave more offspring, so the genes underlying their advantageous traits increase in frequency.

4. Adaptation  
   • Over multiple generations, the cumulative effect of favoring beneficial traits leads a population to become better suited—or adapted—to its environment.  
   • Adaptations can be anatomical (e.g., thicker fur in cold climates), physiological (e.g., enzyme variants that break down toxins), or behavioral (e.g., mating displays that attract partners).

5. Long-Term Outcomes  
   • Complex adaptations can evolve through a series of small, advantageous changes.  
   • Natural selection can drive speciation: when populations of the same species become reproductively isolated and diverge genetically, new species may form.  
   • It contributes to the vast biodiversity we observe today.

6. Real-World Examples and Applications  
   • Medicine: Overuse of antibiotics selects for resistant bacterial strains. Understanding these dynamics guides better treatment protocols.  
   • Agriculture: Plant and animal breeders harness natural variation to develop high-yield or disease-resistant crops and livestock.  
   • Conservation Biology: Knowing which traits are advantageous in changing habitats helps manage endangered species and preserve genetic diversity.

By continually “weeding out” less favorable variations and amplifying traits that improve survival and reproduction, natural selection shapes life’s diversity and drives evolutionary change.
